# Peridot Agent

- Read `PERIDOT_SPEC_v1.md` before implementation work. Treat it as the product architecture source of truth.
- Keep changes scoped to one logical implementation unit and inspect existing files before editing.
- The active implementation has progressed beyond the original seven sessions; use `docs/agents/implementation-playbook.md` to map new work to the closest session area.
- Rust workspace changes should leave these checks passing:
  - `cargo fmt --all --check`
  - `cargo clippy --workspace -- -D warnings`
  - `cargo test --workspace`
- Keep crate responsibilities narrow. Shared types belong in `peridot-common`; use trait boundaries for providers, tools, subagents, scanners, verification, and persistence.
- All user-facing TUI strings flow through `peridot_tui::tr(PhraseKey, Locale)`.
- When touching multi-session routing, read `.peridot/skills/multisession-orchestration/SKILL.md` if present.
- Do not bypass command blocklists, path sandboxing, AGENTS boundaries, prompt-injection tagging, or permission gates for convenience.
